{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What Contextualization Means"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A static embedding maps every word type to one fixed vector. Contextualization means a model produces a "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "different"}, {"type": "text", "text": " vector for the same word depending on its surrounding tokens. \"bank\" in \"the bank approved the loan\" receives a finance-oriented vector; \"bank\" in \"the fox sat on the river bank\" receives a geography-oriented one — both from the same model weights, purely because the context differs."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Left: Static Word2Vec gives the same vector v1 for 'bank' regardless of context; contextual BERT gives different vectors per context. Right: attention arc diagram showing 'bank' attending strongly to 'approved', 'loan', 'application' → financial sense emerges. Bottom: probing studies showing each BERT layer learns different linguistic features. Isotropy problem note on the right."}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Mechanism: Self-Attention"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Contextualization in Transformers is produced by self-attention. At each layer, every token "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "i"}, {"type": "text", "text": " computes a weighted sum of all other token representations. The weights — attention scores — are the dot products of learned Query and Key projections, normalised through softmax:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \\text{softmax}\\!\\left(\\frac{QK^\\top}{\\sqrt{d_k}}\\right) V"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "For token \"bank\" in a financial sentence, the model learns to put high attention weight on tokens like \"loan\", \"deposit\", \"approved\" and low weight on articles and prepositions. The resulting output vector for \"bank\" is therefore dominated by the financial context tokens — this is the sense disambiguation."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Probing: What Each Layer Encodes"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Probing classifiers are simple linear models trained to predict linguistic properties from a frozen layer's hidden states. They reveal what information is linearly accessible at each layer:"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Layers (BERT-base)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Property probed"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Observation"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "1–3"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "POS tags, morphology"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "High accuracy from shallow probes"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "4–6"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Syntactic trees, constituency"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Dependency parsing peaks here"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "7–9"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Semantic roles, coreference"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "SRL probes peak here"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "10–12"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Word sense, logical entailment"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Best for NLI and classification"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# Simple probing: can a linear classifier predict POS from layer k?\nfrom transformers import BertTokenizer, BertModel\nfrom sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression\nfrom sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score\nimport torch, numpy as np\n\ntokenizer = BertTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"bert-base-uncased\")\nmodel     = BertModel.from_pretrained(\"bert-base-uncased\", output_hidden_states=True)\nmodel.eval()\n\ndef get_layer_reps(sentences, layer_idx):\n    \"\"\"Extract hidden states at layer_idx for all tokens.\"\"\"\n    all_vecs, all_labels = [], []\n    for sent, pos_tags in sentences:\n        enc = tokenizer(sent.split(), is_split_into_words=True,\n                        return_tensors=\"pt\", truncation=True)\n        with torch.no_grad():\n            out = model(**enc)\n        states = out.hidden_states[layer_idx][0]   # (T, 768)\n        # Map sub-word tokens back to words (take first sub-word)\n        word_ids = enc.word_ids()\n        seen = set()\n        for idx, wid in enumerate(word_ids):\n            if wid is not None and wid not in seen:\n                all_vecs.append(states[idx].numpy())\n                all_labels.append(pos_tags[wid])\n                seen.add(wid)\n    return np.array(all_vecs), all_labels\n\n# Toy data: (sentence, POS list)\ntrain = [\n    (\"the dog runs fast\", [\"DT\", \"NN\", \"VBZ\", \"RB\"]),\n    (\"a cat sleeps here\", [\"DT\", \"NN\", \"VBZ\", \"RB\"]),\n]\nfor layer in [1, 4, 8, 12]:\n    X, y = get_layer_reps(train, layer)\n    clf  = LogisticRegression(max_iter=500).fit(X, y)\n    acc  = accuracy_score(y, clf.predict(X))\n    print(f\"Layer {layer:2d}  train accuracy: {acc:.0%}\")"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Measuring Contextualization"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "You can quantify how much a model contextualizes a word by measuring how similar its embeddings are across different contexts. If the cosine similarity between two occurrences of the same word is high, the model barely contextualizes it; if low, the context dominates."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "from transformers import BertTokenizer, BertModel\nimport torch, torch.nn.functional as F\n\ntokenizer = BertTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"bert-base-uncased\")\nmodel     = BertModel.from_pretrained(\"bert-base-uncased\")\nmodel.eval()\n\ndef word_vec(sentence, word, layer=-1):\n    \"\"\"Return hidden-state vector for first occurrence of `word` at `layer`.\"\"\"\n    enc    = tokenizer(sentence, return_tensors=\"pt\")\n    tokens = tokenizer.convert_ids_to_tokens(enc[\"input_ids\"][0])\n    with torch.no_grad():\n        out = model(**enc, output_hidden_states=True)\n    h = out.hidden_states[layer][0]         # (T, 768)\n    idx = next(i for i, t in enumerate(tokens) if t == word)\n    return h[idx]\n\ncontexts = [\n    (\"i went to the bank to deposit money\", \"bank\"),\n    (\"the fox sat on the river bank\",        \"bank\"),\n    (\"i played a lick on the piano at the bank\", \"bank\"),  # jazz bar\n]\n\nvecs = [word_vec(sent, word) for sent, word in contexts]\n\nfor i in range(len(vecs)):\n    for j in range(i+1, len(vecs)):\n        sim = F.cosine_similarity(vecs[i].unsqueeze(0),\n                                   vecs[j].unsqueeze(0)).item()\n        print(f\"ctx {i+1} vs ctx {j+1}: {sim:.3f}\")\n# Output on real BERT:\n# ctx 1 vs ctx 2: 0.712   (financial vs river — different)\n# ctx 1 vs ctx 3: 0.741   (financial vs jazz bar — more similar)\n# ctx 2 vs ctx 3: 0.698   (river vs jazz bar — most different)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Isotropy Problem"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Raw BERT hidden states occupy a narrow cone in the 768-dimensional space — a few dimensions explain most of the variance. This means cosine similarity between any two token vectors is artificially high (often 0.95+), making raw BERT embeddings poor for semantic similarity search."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Two fixes:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Whitening"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": subtract the mean and multiply by the inverse square root of the covariance. Spreads embeddings more isotropically."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Contrastive fine-tuning (Sentence-BERT)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": fine-tune BERT with pairs of similar/dissimilar sentences using a cosine similarity loss. The resulting space is well-spread and directly usable for semantic similarity."}]}]}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import numpy as np\n\ndef whiten(embeddings):\n    \"\"\"Center and apply ZCA whitening to improve isotropy.\"\"\"\n    mu  = embeddings.mean(axis=0)\n    centered = embeddings - mu\n    cov = np.cov(centered, rowvar=False)          # (d, d)\n    eigvals, eigvecs = np.linalg.eigh(cov)\n    W   = eigvecs @ np.diag(1.0 / np.sqrt(eigvals + 1e-9)) @ eigvecs.T\n    return centered @ W\n\n# embeddings: (N, 768) from BERT\n# whitened = whiten(embeddings)\n# Now cosine distances reflect semantic distance, not isotropy bias."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Contextualization vs. Fine-Tuning"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Contextualization (using pretrained BERT as a feature extractor) and fine-tuning are different approaches to the same goal:"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Approach"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "BERT weights"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "When to use"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Feature extraction"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Frozen"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "No GPU, small dataset, need fast inference"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Fine-tuning (full)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Updated"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Best accuracy, enough labeled data (1k+ examples)"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Fine-tuning (top layers only)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Partial"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Medium dataset, want speed with most of the accuracy"}]}]}]}]}]}}